T1  - Derationalizing tariffs with specialized intermediate inputs and differentiated final goods
AU  - Markusen, James R.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 28
IS  - 3
SP  - 375
EP  - 383
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/05/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(90)90010-J
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219969090010J
AB  - Existing analyses of differentiated products suggest that a small tariff must be welfare improving, as a positive terms-of-trade effect and an increase in the number of domestic varieties outweighs the loss of foreign varieties. This result appears to be due to an arbitrary assumption that the intra-sectoral elasticity of substitution in consumption exceeds the inter-sectoral elasticity. This paper demonstrates that complementarity among specialized inputs (or differentiated final goods) implies that a small tariff can derationalize production sufficiently such that the number of domestic inputs/goods falls and welfare is reduced.
