T1  - Compositional effects of government spending in a two-country, two-sector production model
AU  - Durlauf, Steven N.
AU  - Staiger, Robert W.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 28
IS  - 3
SP  - 333
EP  - 347
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/05/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(90)90007-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199690900079
AB  - We employ a two-country, two-sector, two-period, Heckscher-Ohlin model to analyze the production-side channels through which a change in the composition of government spending in one country affects real exchange rates, rental rates, and current account balances throughout the world. With one traded and one non-traded consumption good, the model highlights the way in which the world capital stock reshuffles internationally in response to changes in the composition of government spending. These international capital flows correspond to temporary current account imbalances, and serve as the transmission mechanism linking real exchange rate changes at home and abroad.
ER  - 
